a(S'He moved from the H tel Carrel to the Caf  de la Gare on 7 May,[72] having befriended the proprietors, Joseph and Marie Ginoux. The Yellow House had to be furnished before he could fully move in, but Van Gogh was able to use it as a studio.[73] He wanted a gallery to display his work, a series of paintings including Van Gogh\'s Chair (1888), Bedroom in Arles (1888), The Night Caf  (1888), Cafe Terrace at Night (September 1888), Starry Night Over the Rhone (1888), and Still Life: Vase with Twelve Sunflowers (1888), all intended to form the d coration for the Yellow House.[74] Van Gogh wrote that with The Night Caf  he tried "to express the idea that the caf  is a place where one can ruin oneself, go mad, or commit a crime."[75] Moreover, he also wanted to express the terrible passions of humanity by means of red and green.[76] When he visited Saintes-Maries-de-la-Mer that June, he gave lessons to a Zouave second lieutenant Paul-Eug ne Milliet[77]  and painted boats on the sea and the village.[78] MacKnight introduced Van Gogh to Eug ne Boch, a Belgian painter who stayed at times in Fontvieille, and the two exchanged visits in July.[79]'
