a(S'Philosopher Edward S. Casey (1996) describes: "The very word culture meant "place tilled" in Middle English, and the same word goes back to Latin colere, "to inhabit, care for, till, worship" and cultus, "A cult, especially a religious one." To be cultural, to have a culture, is to inhabit a place sufficiently intensive to cultivate it   to be responsible for it, to respond to it, to attend to it caringly."[8]'
