a(S'The bossa nova style was pioneered by Brazilians Jo o Gilberto and Ant nio Carlos Jobim, and was made popular by Elizete Cardoso\'s recording of "Chega de Saudade" on the Can  o do Amor Demais LP. Gilberto\'s initial releases, and the 1959 film Black Orpheus, achieved significant popularity in Latin America; this spread to North America via visiting American jazz musicians. The resulting recordings by Charlie Byrd and Stan Getz cemented bossa nova\'s popularity and led to a worldwide boom, with 1963\'s Getz/Gilberto, numerous recordings by famous jazz performers such as Ella Fitzgerald and Frank Sinatra, and the eventual entrenchment of the bossa nova style as a lasting influence in world music.'
