p33503
g32336
tp33504
a(S'Operating systems that support hierarchical filesystems (practically all modern ones) implement a form of caching to RAM of recent pathnames lookups. In the Unix world, this is usually called Directory Name Lookup Cache (DNLC), although it is called dcache on Linux.[5]'
p33505
g32336
tp33506
a(g34
g32336
tp33507
a(S'For local filesystems, DNLC entries normally expire only under pressure from other more recent entries. For network file systems a coherence mechanism is necessary to ensure that entries have not been invalidated by other clients.[5]'
