a(S'Number of names per file[edit]'
p34234
g32336
tp34235
a(S'Unix-like file systems allow a file to have more than one name; in traditional Unix-style file systems, the names are hard links to the file\'s inode or equivalent. Windows supports hard links on NTFS file systems, and provides the command fsutil in Windows XP, and mklink in later versions, for creating them.[7][8] Hard links are different from Windows shortcuts, Mac OS aliases, or symbolic links. The introduction of LFNs with VFAT allowed filename aliases. For example, longfi~1.??? with a maximum of eight plus three characters was a filename alias of "long file name.???" as a way to conform to 8.3 limitations for older programs.'
p34236
g32336
tp34237
a(g34
