a(S'Length restrictions[edit]'
p34245
g32336
tp34246
a(S'Some filesystems restrict the length of filenames. In some cases, these lengths apply to the entire file name, as in 44 characters on IBM S/370.[9] In other cases, the length limits may apply to particular portions of the filename, such as the name of a file in a directory, or a directory name. For example, 9 (e.g., 8-bit FAT in Standalone Disk BASIC), 11 (e.g. FAT12, FAT16, FAT32 in DOS), 14 (e.g. early Unix), 21 (Human68K), 31, 30 (e.g. Apple DOS 3.2 and 3.3), 15 (e.g. Apple ProDOS), 44 (e.g. IBM S/370),[9] or 255 (e.g. early Berkeley Unix) characters or bytes. Length limits often result from assigning fixed space in a filesystem to storing components of names, so increasing limits often requires an incompatible change, as well as reserving more space.'
p34247
g32336
tp34248
a(g34
g32336
tp34249
a(S'A particular issue with filesystems that store information in nested directories is that it may be possible to create a file whose total name exceeds implementation limits, since length checking may apply only to individual parts of the name rather than the entire name. Many Windows applications are limited to a MAX_PATH value of 260, but Windows file names can easily exceed this limit [1].'
p34250
g32336
tp34251
a(g34
g32336
tp34252
a(S'Filename extensions[edit]'
p34253
g32336
tp34254
a(S'Many file systems, including FAT, NTFS, and VMS systems, allow a filename extension that consists of one or more characters following the last period in the filename, dividing the filename into two parts: a base name or stem and an extension or suffix used by some applications to indicate the file type. Multiple output files created by an application use the same basename and various extensions. For example, a compiler might use the extension FOR for source input file (for Fortran code), OBJ for the object output and LST for the listing. Although there are some common extensions, they are arbitrary and a different application might use REL and RPT. On filesystems that do not segregate the extension, files will often have a longer extension such as html.'
p34255
g32336
tp34256
a(g34
g32336
tp34257
a(S'Encoding interoperability[edit]'
p34258
g32336
tp34259
a(S'There is no general encoding standard for filenames.'
p34260
g32336
tp34261
a(g34
g32336
tp34262
a(S'Because file names have to be exchanged between software environments (think network file transfer, file system storage, backup and file synchronization software, configuration management, data compression and archiving, etc.), it is very important not to lose file name information between applications. This led to wide adoption of Unicode as a standard for encoding file names, although legacy software might be non-Unicode-aware.'
p34263
g32336
tp34264
a(g34
g32336
tp34265
a(S'Encoding indication interoperability[edit]'
p34266
g32336
tp34267
a(S'Crystal Clear app kedit.svg'
p34268
g32336
tp34269
a(S"This section may need to be rewritten entirely to comply with Wikipedia's quality standards. You can help. The discussion page may contain suggestions. (September 2012)"
p34270
g32336
tp34271
a(S'Traditionally, filenames allowed any character in their filenames as long as they were file system safe.[2] Although this permitted the use of any encoding, and thus allowed the representation of any local text on any local system, it caused many interoperability issues.'
p34272
g32336
tp34273
a(g34
g32336
tp34274
a(S'A filename could be stored using different byte strings in distinct systems within a single country, such as if one used Japanese Shift JIS encoding and another Japanese EUC encoding. Conversion was not possible as most systems did not expose a description of the encoding used for a filename as part of the extended file information. This forced costly filename encoding guessing with each file access.[2]'
p34275
g32336
tp34276
a(g34
g32336
tp34277
a(S'A solution was to adopt Unicode as the encoding for filenames.'
p34278
g32336
tp34279
a(g34
g32336
tp34280
a(S'In the Mac OS however, encoding of the filename was stored with the filename attributes.[2]'
p34281
g32336
tp34282
a(g34
g32336
tp34283
a(S'Unicode interoperability[edit]'
p34284
g32336
tp34285
a(S'The Unicode standard solves the encoding determination issue.'
p34286
g32336
tp34287
a(g34
g32336
tp34288
a(S'Nonetheless, some limited interoperability issues remain, such as normalization (equivalence), or the Unicode version in use. For instance, UDF is limited to Unicode 2.0; Mac OS applies NFD Unicode normalization and is optionally case-sensitive (case-insensitive by default.) Filename maximum length is not standard and might depend on the code unit size. Although it is a serious issue, in most cases this is a limited one.[2]'
p34289
g32336
tp34290
a(g34
g32336
tp34291
a(S'On Linux, this means the filename is not enough to open a file: additionally, the exact byte representation of the filename on the storage device is needed. This can be solved at the application level, with some tricky normalization calls.[10]'
p34292
g32336
tp34293
a(g34
g32336
tp34294
a(S'The issue of Unicode equivalence is known as "normalized-name collision". A solution is the Non-normalizing Unicode Composition Awareness used in the Subversion and Apache technical communities.[11] This solution does not normalize paths in the repository. Paths are only normalized for the purpose of comparisons. Nonetheless, some communities have patented this strategy, forbidding its use by other communities.[clarification needed]'
p34295
g32336
tp34296
a(g34
